\begin_layout Standard
The Catmull-Clark subdivision transformation is used to smooth a surface
 as the limit of a sequence of subdivision steps
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stam1998"

\end_inset

.
 This process is governed by properties of B-splines curve from multivariate
 spline theory
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Loop1987"

\end_inset

.
 This method does a recursive subdivision transformation that refines the
 model into a linear interpolation that approximates a smooth surface.
 The smoothness of the model is automatically guaranteed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeRose1998"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Catmull-Clark subdivision surface methods generate smooth and continuous
 models from a coarse model and produce results quickly due to the simplicity
 of implementation, but with these methods is not easy to make changes to
 the global curvature of the model.
 If we use Catmull-Clark subdivision surfaces and curvature enhancement
 for modeling from coarse models with few vertices can generate families
 of shapes changing a single parameter, this would allow an artist to choose
 the model from a similar set of options that best meets his/her needs without
 having to change each one of the control vertices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our method allows the use of vertex weight paint over the control points.
 The weights can be applied to a coarse model, then to perform a Catmull-Clark
 subdivision where weights are interpolated, producing weights with smooth
 changes in the zones of influence, so the obtained curvature is much softer
 at those areas as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Subdivision-Cups"

\end_inset

.c.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lineal_System_with_wp"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with weights corresponding to each vertex.
 Weights at each vertex produce a different solution for this reason the
 matrix is placed in the diffusion equation, as families that are generated
 may change substantially with weighted of specific control points.
\end_layout

